Dear Michael, dear Lukasz,

Thank you very much for your swift response and your input!

>> I suspect you will see large standard errors for the coefficients in
>> your multimoderator analysis.>

Yes, this is precisely the case. The standard errors are much larger in the multi-moderator model and the resulting CIs are very wide.

>> I think that may be a scientific question - are we interested in such
>> effects? Interpretation is also difficult if any of the moderators is
>> strongly associated with others.

There is limited interest because I am rather interested in how a moderator impacts the results overall than how a particular and small subset of study characteristic combinations impacts the outcome. The VIFs for several predictors (and associated changes in SE/CI) are pretty high, making a simultaneous estimation questionable in the first place.

Thank you also for pointing me to relevant resources. 

Based on the resources and the output, I think the multi-moderator model would only be of limited use here.

Thanks,
Max

